statement:
There are n lamps L0, L1, … , L_{n−1} in a circle (n > 1), where we denote L_{n+k} = L_k. A lamp at all times is either on or off. Perform steps s0, s1, … as follows: at step si, if L_{i−1} is lit, switch Li from on to off or vice versa; otherwise do nothing. Initially all lamps are on.

Show that:
(a) There is a positive integer M(n) such that after M(n) steps all the lamps are on again;
(b) If n = 2^k, we can take M(n) = n^2 − 1;
(c) If n = 2^k + 1, we can take M(n) = n^2 − n + 1.
